text.tspan: Heartbreak is a 2D sidescrolling
rhythm game, where you play as
The Protagonist who has just had
his heart stolen and is now on a
mission to retrieve it.
During the game, you have a
choice between two input
methods: a one button input
method where you jump between
platforms, and a four-button
input method where you have
four lanes on the screen and you
must navigate between them.
There are also enemies you must
avoid, and coins you can collect
throughout the level. There is a
health bar which will decrease as
you get hit by enemies, and a
score bar which gives you points
based on how accurate the inputs
are with the rhythm. There are
also many options that can be
adjusted to make the game easier
or harder.
MOTIVATIONS
Rhythm games are a genre of
video games where the player
has to time their inputs
correctly to the rhythm of a
music track. Typical rhythm games
involve high-speed gameplay and
challenges the player to compete
to get a higher score, and offers
a unique way to experience music
within the video game format.
There has also been a surge of
popularity in the rhythm game
genre in recent years, as the
genre can be merged with other
genres to create very unique
hybrid games.
My goal for this game was to
create a simple rhythm game,
and to focus on the mechanics to
allow me to understand the basic
components for a rhythm game,
which will allow me to create
more complex rhythm games in
the future.
I decided to make a 2D
sidescroller rhythm game as the
simple design needed for a
sidescroller will allow me to focus
my attention on the rhythm game
aspects of the game. I used Unity
as my game engine as there are
countless rhythm games made in
Unity which meant that there
were many samples of how to add
the rhythm game mechanics to
the game that I could use.
The main issue I had to tackle
was making the game sync with
the audio, as this was essential
for every other system in the
game. As Unity has its own time
system, I had to develop a system
outside of the in-built time system
to regulate the timings of the
inputs, while also being able to
interact with Unity's systems, for
example the player movement.
I also wanted to focus on
accessibility options as I think it's
important that as many people as
possible can play video games, and
it allows me to expand my
knowledge of Unity mechanics. I
added the option to have a visual
cue for the BPM, as well as the
option for a metronome for an
audio cue. and the option to
increase the timing windows for
the inputs. My goal with including
these is not to make the game
easier, but to allow players to
have assistance if needed.
